1
00:00:02,730 --> 00:00:10,720
I want to continue the exploration of the four divine abodes, which in Pali are known as the Brahma Vihara.

2
00:00:11,881 --> 00:00:17,788
The focus tonight is on Metta, which is the basis for all the Brahma Vihara.

3
00:00:19,370 --> 00:00:24,615
Metta is often translated as loving kindness, or more simply as goodwill.

4
00:00:25,998 --> 00:00:29,801
It can also be described as inoffensiveness and non-harming.

5
00:00:31,097 --> 00:00:40,078
In positive terms, it describes an open-hearted attitude, warmth, friendliness, benevolence, care.

6
00:00:41,813 --> 00:00:46,802
The analogy the Buddha gives is the ideal mother's love for her only child.

7
00:00:47,984 --> 00:00:54,277
She's totally devoted, giving attention and affection without expecting anything in return.

8
00:00:55,558 --> 00:00:59,646
She forgives misbehaviour instantly and harbours no resentment.

9
00:01:00,588 --> 00:01:02,371
That is the ideal we have to aim at.

10
00:01:02,953 --> 00:01:03,854
Quite a challenge.

11
00:01:05,353 --> 00:01:10,400
True Meta is based on altruism rather than mundane self-interest.

12
00:01:11,441 --> 00:01:21,373
It is universal, applying to strangers, animals and other beings, as much as to ourselves and our closest family and friends.

13
00:01:22,694 --> 00:01:26,620
To those who have wronged us as much as to those who have cared for us.

14
00:01:28,102 --> 00:01:32,212
When the heart is filled with matter, it brings out the best in us and others.

15
00:01:33,516 --> 00:01:34,618
Life seems simple.

16
00:01:35,221 --> 00:01:43,882
We smile, we're interested in the other person, we're easily pleased, we speak and act benevolently in any company.

17
00:01:45,870 --> 00:01:50,737
Fall from grace only comes when we perceive others or the world as threatening.

18
00:01:52,019 --> 00:01:58,971
All of our spiritual practice is aimed towards understanding that our essential nature cannot be threatened.

19
00:02:00,412 --> 00:02:03,858
When we are fully enlightened, metta will be our natural state.

20
00:02:04,698 --> 00:02:10,527
Till then, metta practice helps us coax and cajole ourselves in this direction.

21
00:02:12,044 --> 00:02:16,133
So we don't have to feel happy and benevolent to practice metta.

22
00:02:17,054 --> 00:02:21,524
It's the kindly thought or act that counts, not the feeling.

23
00:02:22,586 --> 00:02:30,222
We can feel miserable, but still do our best to make things pleasant and easy for ourselves and others.

24
00:02:31,770 --> 00:02:44,616
It is said that the Buddha taught the Metta Sutta to monks whose forest dwelling was also the home of evil spirits who were trying to frighten them away with noises, visions and stinking orders.

25
00:02:45,354 --> 00:02:52,605
So when the monks started practicing Metta, they were probably feeling scared stiff rather than any way kindly.

26
00:02:53,667 --> 00:03:00,276
Nevertheless, the spirits began to calm down and eventually to worship the monks as their benefactors.

27
00:03:01,478 --> 00:03:06,645
Metta softens not only our own hearts, but also the hearts of those around us.

28
00:03:09,028 --> 00:03:12,274
The far enemy of Metta is El Ilwil.

29
00:03:13,942 --> 00:03:17,741
which can manifest in many different hues and intensities.

30
00:03:18,616 --> 00:03:30,372
Mild irritation, impatience, exasperation, despising, fear, blame, hatred and all the way up to murderous rage.

31
00:03:31,413 --> 00:03:34,978
Its expression depends on personality and circumstances.

32
00:03:36,159 --> 00:03:38,263
Sometimes there is an explosion of anger.

33
00:03:39,084 --> 00:03:41,026
Sometimes anger is more contained.

34
00:03:41,907 --> 00:03:47,474
Coldness, withdrawal, sulking, refusing to cooperate.

35
00:03:47,455 --> 00:03:50,786
It can be expressed openly or more subtly.

36
00:03:51,769 --> 00:03:59,051
Sighing heavily, grimacing, speaking ill of the person behind their back, undermining them.

37
00:04:00,094 --> 00:04:06,324
All expressions of anger, open or subtle, endanger our relationships.

38
00:04:07,425 --> 00:04:11,290
Well-meaning friends become wary of us and may lose touch altogether.

39
00:04:12,532 --> 00:04:22,086
On the other hand, anger attracts people with a negative disposition, who then further exacerbate our own ill-will.

40
00:04:24,579 --> 00:04:31,492
Negativity escalates as tit for tat reactions spark between quarrelling parties.

41
00:04:33,036 --> 00:04:38,266
It can spread like wildfire and turn into chronic feuds and gangland violence.

42
00:04:39,228 --> 00:04:42,132
On a large scale we end up with the atrocities of war.

43
00:04:43,480 --> 00:04:47,964
Ill will can also be directed inwards towards ourselves.

44
00:04:48,906 --> 00:04:57,113
We blame ourselves for our lack of success, our financial problems, our poor health and all the other dukkha in our lives.

45
00:04:58,134 --> 00:05:08,526
This might not get us into trouble that goes with outwardly directed anger, but it can be equally destructive for our well-being.

46
00:05:10,295 --> 00:05:18,403
As there is no effective opposition, we can hammer ourselves black and blue without any reprimand.

47
00:05:19,906 --> 00:05:25,091
Over time, habits of self-blame can lead to chronic anxiety and depression.

48
00:05:25,952 --> 00:05:29,817
We are afraid of our own judgement and feel completely hopeless about life.

49
00:05:32,281 --> 00:05:34,142
The near enemy is attachment.

50
00:05:35,463 --> 00:05:38,648
In this case, we are clinging to the other in a needy way.

51
00:05:39,420 --> 00:05:45,370
It could be great passion, the beloved becomes the centre and meaning of a person's whole existence.

52
00:05:46,851 --> 00:05:50,497
It could be a mother over-protecting her child.

53
00:05:51,639 --> 00:05:59,310
At a simpler level, most human relationships involve some degree of anxiety about keeping the relationship on friendly terms.

54
00:06:00,533 --> 00:06:04,399
Attachment can manifest in a variety of ways.

55
00:06:04,379 --> 00:06:12,588
We might worry about our beloved's relationships with other people, jealously guarding our own share of their time and affection.

56
00:06:13,430 --> 00:06:17,154
We buy them gifts, delightedly anticipating their gratitude.

57
00:06:18,555 --> 00:06:21,839
If they go on holidays, we secretly hope they'll miss us.

58
00:06:22,540 --> 00:06:27,146
We chatter inanely, anxious for their interest and approval.

59
00:06:28,762 --> 00:06:35,834
While attachment is a normal aspect of human relationships, we need to be careful not to foster it.

60
00:06:37,117 --> 00:06:40,081
If it gets out of control it damages the relationship.

61
00:06:40,903 --> 00:06:52,122
The needy person neglects their own development, projecting all their inner goodness and strength onto the other, who in turn feels burdened by those projections and needs.

62
00:06:53,519 --> 00:06:58,487
Metta meditation is a powerful antidote to all the miseries described above.

63
00:06:59,430 --> 00:07:03,497
Here we wish ourselves and others well in four areas of life.

64
00:07:04,358 --> 00:07:11,291
Basic safety, physical health, mental well-being and social working family life.

65
00:07:12,975 --> 00:07:22,105
The phrases are some variant on may you be safe, well, happy, living in harmony with the world.

66
00:07:23,266 --> 00:07:27,110
We direct these toward all the categories described last night.

67
00:07:28,050 --> 00:07:32,654
If the phrases don't work for you, then try to imagine the person in a happy situation.

68
00:07:33,555 --> 00:07:38,761
Alternatively, the breath may carry an embodied sense of goodwill.

69
00:07:40,903 --> 00:07:42,004
Almost as if

70
00:07:42,574 --> 00:07:46,201
You're blowing up a balloon of goodwill with each breath.

71
00:07:47,382 --> 00:07:52,189
Again, this is completely valid as a Metta practice.

72
00:07:52,209 --> 00:07:56,197
All the hindrances we experience in Vipassana can emerge in Metta.

73
00:07:57,158 --> 00:07:59,661
Wandering mind, dullness, doubt.

74
00:08:00,564 --> 00:08:07,113
In the first instance, we just acknowledge these and bring our attention back to generating Metta.

75
00:08:07,093 --> 00:08:11,744
Remember what we said yesterday about dodging round the hindrances.

76
00:08:12,444 --> 00:08:16,353
Some of these dodges we've already learnt in Vipassana.

77
00:08:16,372 --> 00:08:20,341
Opening our eyes, standing up for dullness and lethargy.

78
00:08:21,103 --> 00:08:26,654
Calming ourselves for a few breaths for the wandering mind, restlessness and worry.

79
00:08:26,634 --> 00:08:39,105
If the hindrance persists, we switch attention back to the easiest of the meta categories and re-establish goodwill before reconnecting with the more challenging category.

80
00:08:40,488 --> 00:08:44,677
Basically, do whatever you can to make things easy for yourself.

81
00:08:46,042 --> 00:08:52,068
Perhaps the greatest challenge is when all our grudges reappear the moment we think of a person.

82
00:08:53,070 --> 00:08:57,534
Even our best friend, or else we start worrying what they think of us.

83
00:08:58,556 --> 00:08:59,657
This is quite natural.

84
00:08:59,697 --> 00:09:02,780
It's part of the purification process.

85
00:09:03,642 --> 00:09:09,628
Keep reminding yourself that there doesn't have to be a feeling of loving kindness.

86
00:09:10,249 --> 00:09:13,111
It's the willingness to keep trying that counts.

87
00:09:13,732 --> 00:09:21,485
If you keep getting carried away into angry, anxious thoughts, direct Metta towards yourself in the shade of compassion.

88
00:09:22,226 --> 00:09:29,138
Example, may I be free from ill will or may I be free from anxiety?

89
00:09:30,099 --> 00:09:32,602
Stay with this for the full session if needed.

90
00:09:34,371 --> 00:09:38,580
What is more troublesome is when the near enemy goes unnoticed.

91
00:09:39,701 --> 00:09:50,101
We're wishing everyone well, heart soaring with goodwill, but subtly identifying with that sense of goodness and friendliness.

92
00:09:51,365 --> 00:09:53,870
We might only notice the problem afterwards.

93
00:09:54,711 --> 00:09:57,859
We're beaming radiantly at our family over breakfast.

94
00:09:58,720 --> 00:10:02,327
But when someone makes a snappy response, our bubble bursts.

95
00:10:03,210 --> 00:10:05,695
The fall from grace can be very sore.

96
00:10:06,215 --> 00:10:07,596
and bring out the worst in us.

97
00:10:08,116 --> 00:10:09,418
Suddenly we hate everyone.

98
00:10:10,379 --> 00:10:15,803
If you notice this pattern, try taking it easier during Metta practice.

99
00:10:16,583 --> 00:10:22,208
Allow a few breaths between each good wish and be sensitive to feelings of friendliness.

100
00:10:22,669 --> 00:10:24,211
Acknowledge and appreciate them.

101
00:10:24,572 --> 00:10:29,875
Then they can energize and strengthen your Metta without leading you into delusion.

102
00:10:30,897 --> 00:10:36,221
It helps to keep in mind that we're not practicing Metta in order to feel good.

103
00:10:36,201 --> 00:10:37,807
feelings come and go.

104
00:10:37,826 --> 00:10:45,975
What matters is that we're willing to gently nudge our attitude towards goodwill in all circumstances.

105
00:10:47,895 --> 00:10:55,827
On the opposite end of the spectrum, we can judge our goodwill to be so paltry that we believe we're not really practicing at all.

106
00:10:56,730 --> 00:11:00,395
This is self-doubt, doubting our own powers of goodness.

107
00:11:01,336 --> 00:11:04,481
It underlies the fear of failure we spoke of last night.

108
00:11:05,683 --> 00:11:11,472
In the first instance, just carry on regardless of any belittling comments you hear.

109
00:11:11,452 --> 00:11:19,299
Perhaps you can smile at them or insist, this is enough, I will not despise my goodwill offering.

110
00:11:20,301 --> 00:11:25,365
Try putting a hand on your heart or any gesture you find supportive.

111
00:11:26,447 --> 00:11:32,993
If that doesn't work, try self-compassion, reassuring yourself over and over of your essential goodness.

112
00:11:34,274 --> 00:11:38,337
Just as the ideal mother would reassure her only child.

113
00:11:39,652 --> 00:11:51,018
Alternatively, shade the goodwill towards equanimity, encouraging yourself to take it easy and don't believe self-doubts belittling judgments.

114
00:11:52,260 --> 00:11:56,951
Instead, see this meditation session as a deep purification.

115
00:11:59,277 --> 00:12:10,417
If none of the suggested remedies for the near or far enemies is working, then switch to Vipassana, acknowledging whatever emotion is coming up.

116
00:12:10,437 --> 00:12:13,142
And don't think of any such session as a failure.

117
00:12:13,823 --> 00:12:21,758
It's a very central and necessary part of metta practice to know when to call a halt and switch to Vipassana.

118
00:12:21,738 --> 00:12:32,517
A successful explorer will often say that their most precious quality wasn't determination or strength, but the ability to turn back when things were too dangerous.

119
00:12:33,658 --> 00:12:37,485
Metta practice is a deep exploration of the heart.

120
00:12:37,505 --> 00:12:44,538
It shows us how threatened we feel deep down, due to our confusion about ultimate reality.

121
00:12:44,519 --> 00:12:54,275
When our Meta can no longer dodge and dive around the demons we've unleashed, we need to respect their power and listen to their story in Vipassana.

122
00:12:57,174 --> 00:13:10,274
In daily life we cultivate metta in acts of friendship, making someone a cup of tea, taking time to visit, or we could join a local club, donate towards a community project.

123
00:13:11,736 --> 00:13:20,769
In all cases we need to keep reminding ourselves that our actions are for our own and others' welfare.

124
00:13:20,750 --> 00:13:34,014
Otherwise we can easily slip into attachment, being friendly so that we'll feel good or that people will like us and then getting a shock when our expectations aren't met.

125
00:13:35,296 --> 00:13:40,385
That shock can lead on to resentment and other manifestations of ill will.

126
00:13:41,548 --> 00:13:43,871
Altruism is quite a tough practice.

127
00:13:44,864 --> 00:13:47,328
I remember my first clear seeing of this.

128
00:13:47,369 --> 00:13:52,477
I was on retreat and noticed a hammer had been left in the garden.

129
00:13:52,958 --> 00:13:55,302
Probably someone forgot it after doing some work.

130
00:13:56,144 --> 00:13:58,970
I picked it up and brought it back to the tool shed.

131
00:13:59,691 --> 00:14:05,061
I noticed how strongly I wanted to leave a note explaining where I'd found it and what I'd assumed.

132
00:14:05,942 --> 00:14:08,727
But I also felt the neediness underlying this.

133
00:14:09,873 --> 00:14:13,037
Basically, I wanted them to know how caring and kind I was.

134
00:14:13,057 --> 00:14:20,547
It seemed like such a waste just to leave the hammer back without getting any recognition for my good deed.

135
00:14:21,447 --> 00:14:31,019
But luckily, I had the sense not to encourage my neediness, and I sadly left it back with no note and no mark of recognition.

136
00:14:31,000 --> 00:14:37,168
After that it was easier to spot the bonds of attachment in almost every so-called good deed.

137
00:14:38,029 --> 00:14:40,673
Just seeing was the really important thing.

138
00:14:41,916 --> 00:14:42,836
Then I had a choice.

139
00:14:43,538 --> 00:14:49,066
I could cut out whatever aspects of my good deed were really about getting praise and recognition.

140
00:14:49,807 --> 00:14:58,779
I could acknowledge the sense of loss in all this and I could make the good wish even though this was usually with a tight grimace.

141
00:15:00,480 --> 00:15:04,325
This is an example of how Metta brings up the near and far enemies.

142
00:15:05,245 --> 00:15:14,934
If we find ourselves anxiously anticipating our friend's next words, we need to acknowledge that this is attachment and step back to regain our equilibrium.

143
00:15:16,155 --> 00:15:19,940
Perhaps we just go quiet for a while directing Metta towards ourselves.

144
00:15:20,921 --> 00:15:28,969
Or we might need to remove ourselves physically to avoid the temptation to seek reassurance or otherwise burden them with our needs.

145
00:15:30,738 --> 00:15:36,826
Caring for ourselves builds up the confidence needed to overcome emotional dependency.

146
00:15:37,548 --> 00:15:41,193
We do this in a very deep way when we devote time to meditation.

147
00:15:42,095 --> 00:15:49,004
But every activity, washing, dressing, eating, working is part of caring for our human life.

148
00:15:50,226 --> 00:15:53,731
But we need to remind ourselves that our motivation is kindness.

149
00:15:54,452 --> 00:16:00,221
Otherwise, these easily slip into autopilot and emotional self-neglect.

150
00:16:01,179 --> 00:16:08,109
May I take care of myself happily is a good phrase to remember as we go about our daily activities.

151
00:16:09,870 --> 00:16:13,355
This can bring up another shade of the far enemy.

152
00:16:14,716 --> 00:16:18,942
For myself, the practice around eating has shown up a lot of guilt.

153
00:16:18,962 --> 00:16:27,052
If I find myself looking in the cupboard for a snack, I prefer to do this without any reflection rather than say, may I take care of myself happily.

154
00:16:28,518 --> 00:16:32,501
The reflection brings up all kinds of questions like, do I really need this?

155
00:16:33,222 --> 00:16:34,124
Should I be having this?

156
00:16:35,125 --> 00:16:36,446
Isn't this self-indulgence?

157
00:16:37,986 --> 00:16:43,952
At first, the only way I could deal with the situation was to close the cupboard door and go without that little perk.

158
00:16:45,095 --> 00:16:49,879
And I'd feel pretty bad for having even tried to take a snack.

159
00:16:49,899 --> 00:16:53,722
But then half an hour later, I'd be munching my way through the biscuits anyhow.

160
00:16:54,344 --> 00:16:57,647
The desire would have slipped through and got me to the cupboard.

161
00:16:57,626 --> 00:17:07,009
After a bit of reflection, I started experimenting with mindful indulgence as a way of working more skilfully with the desire and guilt cycle.

162
00:17:08,053 --> 00:17:15,130
I needed to plan a few treats, which were obviously not just for the sake of nourishing the body.

163
00:17:16,712 --> 00:17:19,174
like cheesecake and ice cream.

164
00:17:20,336 --> 00:17:28,403
I would eat it slowly, pausing whenever the guilt surfaced, letting it ebb away into a good wish for my own happiness.

165
00:17:30,145 --> 00:17:45,099
And when the treat was over and the guilt would be persuading me to be very judgmental about my unnecessary indulgence, I would instead thank myself for having given myself this little perk to cheer myself up.

166
00:17:47,627 --> 00:17:53,675
Gradually, this has undermined the automatic guilt which surfaces around pleasure.

167
00:17:55,258 --> 00:18:03,028
I can more willingly resist unnecessary treats and feel grateful that my better judgment overcame the habit of desire.

168
00:18:04,309 --> 00:18:13,061
And I can more easily admit that if I'm feeling a bit low, a biscuit or maybe cheesecake and ice cream will cheer me up.

169
00:18:14,662 --> 00:18:22,772
So in daily life we need to find skilful ways of working around the patterns of ill-will that so easily manifest.

170
00:18:23,815 --> 00:18:38,154
Rather than expect too much of ourselves in the Metta department, in daily life the attempt to practice Metta can also get twisted around to ill-will when we identify with the feeling of Metta.

171
00:18:38,134 --> 00:18:42,267
We want so much to think of ourselves as kindly and benevolent.

172
00:18:43,250 --> 00:18:52,194
But when people who push our buttons show us that we're nothing of the sort, then we fly into a rage at the most petty remark.

173
00:18:52,798 --> 00:18:56,203
So now we have a new reason to hate them.

174
00:18:56,223 --> 00:18:58,066
It's the old problem of identity.

175
00:18:58,847 --> 00:19:04,335
If we start bringing me, a benevolent person, into the equation, we end up in trouble.

176
00:19:05,356 --> 00:19:14,269
We need to keep reminding ourselves that until we're fully enlightened, me will become all kinds of different characters depending on the situation.

177
00:19:15,351 --> 00:19:22,401
The rotten-hearted, fizzling with rage me is our reminder to cultivate self-care.

178
00:19:24,388 --> 00:19:37,757
When our nearest and dearest have managed to push that button and we are on the verge of a blazing row, for example, it's usually best to beat a hasty retreat before we say anything to worsen the situation.

179
00:19:39,829 --> 00:19:50,095
If we say something nasty, which of course seems perfectly justified in the heat of the situation, it ends up making things an awful lot harder for ourselves.

180
00:19:51,076 --> 00:19:57,653
The Buddha put right speech amongst the three steps on morality in the Eightfold Path.

181
00:19:57,633 --> 00:20:08,825
This may be because most of us involved in spiritual development would think carefully before thumping someone or doing any physical deed that would harm them.

182
00:20:09,625 --> 00:20:14,872
But harmful speech comes out so, so easily when we feel threatened.

183
00:20:15,772 --> 00:20:17,855
It can slip out before we've had time to think.

184
00:20:18,596 --> 00:20:24,702
The tongue like a sharp knife kills without drawing blood is an ancient Chinese proverb.

185
00:20:26,134 --> 00:20:33,471
It helps to have a stock phrase in mind like, I can't think clearly about this right now, I'll get back to you later.

186
00:20:33,752 --> 00:20:37,561
Then we go off somewhere quiet to let ourselves fizzle out.

187
00:20:39,112 --> 00:20:43,842
When we've calmed a bit, we often feel the sorrow underlying our bout of rage.

188
00:20:44,743 --> 00:20:57,271
Often this is linked to the truth of anatta, showing us how little control we have over others and even over our own emotions.

189
00:20:59,750 --> 00:21:10,486
Although the facts are, as you have heard a thousand times before, the feeling of not being able to control that which we care about always challenges us to the core.

190
00:21:13,290 --> 00:21:21,403
Rather than give out to ourselves about our limitations, we need to learn to offer ourselves metta in compassionate terms.

191
00:21:22,395 --> 00:21:30,631
For example, some comforting gesture like stroking our hand and reassuring ourselves that it's all okay.

192
00:21:32,013 --> 00:21:40,489
Eventually we may be able to tune into the basic humanity of whoever it was that angered us and wish them to come to no harm.

193
00:21:43,809 --> 00:21:53,922
Let's come now to look at the Buddha's teachings on the value of spiritual friendship, or Kalyana Mita in Pali.

194
00:21:54,846 --> 00:22:04,101
One teaching starts with Ananda remarking that this is half of the holy life Lord, admirable friendship, admirable companionship.

195
00:22:04,422 --> 00:22:09,048
Buddha replied, don't say that Ananda, don't say that.

196
00:22:09,750 --> 00:22:15,960
Admirable friendship, admirable companionship is actually the whole of the holy life.

197
00:22:15,940 --> 00:22:26,251
When a monk has admirable people as friends, companions and colleagues, he can be expected to develop and pursue the noble eightfold path.

198
00:22:27,834 --> 00:22:29,635
At first sight this seems a bit odd.

199
00:22:30,656 --> 00:22:36,784
The Buddha is more often heard advising people to withdraw to some secluded place to meditate.

200
00:22:37,365 --> 00:22:42,009
Now here he is telling Ananda that friendship, companionship is the whole of the holy life.

201
00:22:42,770 --> 00:22:44,292
Sounds great, doesn't it?

202
00:22:44,694 --> 00:22:49,946
Maybe we can just hang about chatting while the Dharma somehow filters in.

203
00:22:50,990 --> 00:22:57,455
But the Sutta doesn't end there and in the next paragraph the Buddha is back to his more usual form.

204
00:22:58,277 --> 00:23:06,244
And how does a monk who has admirable people as friends, companions and colleagues develop and pursue the Noble Eightfold Path?

205
00:23:07,306 --> 00:23:19,798
There is the case where a monk develops right view dependent on seclusion, dependent on dispassion, dependent on cessation resulting in relinquishment.

206
00:23:21,027 --> 00:23:31,172
Right view is the first part of the Noble Eightfold Path and he says the same about all the other parts.

207
00:23:33,531 --> 00:23:37,616
So we still have to do all the usual hard work.

208
00:23:37,636 --> 00:23:42,343
But the point being made here is that the work is done in the context of friendship.

209
00:23:43,523 --> 00:23:46,769
This emphasises the humanity in the Buddhist teaching.

210
00:23:47,650 --> 00:23:56,921
Too often we hear words like seclusion, dispassion and think of the path as a solitary, antisocial, lonely affair.

211
00:23:58,123 --> 00:24:02,407
But here he is placing human friendship as the essential frame for all our work.

212
00:24:03,670 --> 00:24:10,421
He describes a friendship we need for spiritual life as admirable and gives this definition.

213
00:24:10,882 --> 00:24:12,964
And what is meant by admirable friendship?

214
00:24:13,846 --> 00:24:25,967
There is the case where a lay person in whatever town or village he may dwell spends time with householders or householder's sons, young or old, who are advanced in virtue.

215
00:24:26,867 --> 00:24:30,453
He talks with them, engages them in discussions.

216
00:24:31,632 --> 00:24:45,714
The language gets complex from here on, but the gist of it is that the person emulates the best in each of them, copying the generosity of the generous friend, the wisdom of the wise friend and so on.

217
00:24:46,757 --> 00:24:52,205
Basically, we are to seek out virtuous friends, find the best in them and copy that.

218
00:24:53,653 --> 00:24:59,640
If we are lucky enough to have a Dharma group, we already have a source of admirable friendship.

219
00:24:59,660 --> 00:25:01,442
This is such a wonderful gift.

220
00:25:02,103 --> 00:25:09,711
I found a meditation group in the mid-1980s and over the past 30 years they have become my best friends.

221
00:25:10,731 --> 00:25:17,298
When we chat about our various challenges and inspirations in life, we end up framing this in the context of the Dharma.

222
00:25:19,050 --> 00:25:28,030
So quite naturally our attitudes, speech and lifestyle have become better aligned with the Dharma just by spending time in each other's company.

223
00:25:29,413 --> 00:25:36,569
Now let's look at his specific advice to seek out the best in each of our friends and copy that.

224
00:25:37,714 --> 00:25:39,576
At one level that happens naturally.

225
00:25:40,218 --> 00:25:42,480
In any group you get norms for behaviour.

226
00:25:43,682 --> 00:25:51,190
So if getting drunk every night is a badge of honour in your friendship group, then you'll probably feel odd, even a bit ashamed if you're not a drinker.

227
00:25:52,451 --> 00:25:59,519
And the Buddha counsels against making unwise friendships like these, saying they are a drain on our resources.

228
00:26:00,901 --> 00:26:10,926
But amongst our wise friends, generosity, caring for others, going on retreat or daily meditation practice might be badges of honour.

229
00:26:11,969 --> 00:26:17,323
So our own behaviour naturally tends to move up towards the group norm.

230
00:26:19,767 --> 00:26:23,855
So our goodness rubs off on one another at a subconscious level.

231
00:26:24,737 --> 00:26:27,702
Can we also bring that to the level of conscious choice?

232
00:26:28,564 --> 00:26:33,473
Can we actively seek out what's most admirable in our friends and copy that?

233
00:26:34,776 --> 00:26:35,637
Certainly we can.

234
00:26:36,799 --> 00:26:39,665
Though we might often run into obstacles on the way.

235
00:26:40,928 --> 00:26:44,595
Ireland, for example, has been described as a nation of begrudgers.

236
00:26:45,517 --> 00:26:51,949
We seek for the downside in every success story, the cloud behind the silver lining.

237
00:26:51,969 --> 00:27:03,290
To the extent that a begrudging cultural norm rubs its way down to each of us, we find it hard to trust and value goodness in our friends and even in ourselves.

238
00:27:03,270 --> 00:27:10,980
So the Buddha's advice is of valuable balance in any cultural tendency to suspect the worst in everyone.

239
00:27:13,962 --> 00:27:24,736
To take an example, I have some wonderful friends who have a greater capacity than me to smile at human weakness, not get too hung up about it.

240
00:27:25,056 --> 00:27:29,039
My own tendency is to get depressed when I hear someone's making a mess of things.

241
00:27:29,800 --> 00:27:33,025
And when I see my friends smiling, I can find myself wondering,

242
00:27:33,628 --> 00:27:35,070
Do they have no sympathy?

243
00:27:37,012 --> 00:27:46,663
We've talked about this at various stages and I completely trust that their smile is based not on a lack of sympathy but having a wider perspective on the situation.

244
00:27:47,765 --> 00:28:00,378
To put it in Dharma terms, you could say that they see the first noble truth in action, that life involves suffering, but trust that the other three will eventually save the day.

245
00:28:01,304 --> 00:28:12,558
The effort I've had to put into understanding and trusting their perspective illustrates how hard it is for us to value virtues that we haven't developed strongly in ourselves.

246
00:28:14,981 --> 00:28:21,109
Much easier to ignore these or even quietly dismiss them as a vice rather than a virtue.

247
00:28:22,010 --> 00:28:27,057
For example, my tendency to interpret their smiles as lack of sympathy.

248
00:28:28,320 --> 00:28:37,231
Recognising a virtue that we haven't developed strongly ourselves is hard enough, but copying it is even harder.

249
00:28:38,413 --> 00:28:41,175
My laryngectomy operation was a case in point.

250
00:28:42,397 --> 00:28:46,102
My friends were better able than me to see in perspective.

251
00:28:47,384 --> 00:28:51,087
A huge loss, yes, but not a major disaster.

252
00:28:52,486 --> 00:28:58,395
This allowed them to care for me very effectively and incredibly generously throughout the whole episode.

253
00:28:59,557 --> 00:29:04,945
At times, though, my sense of the situation was that all the goodness had gone out of life.

254
00:29:05,586 --> 00:29:07,871
I just couldn't understand how they could be happy.

255
00:29:08,592 --> 00:29:09,693
It felt like treachery.

256
00:29:11,676 --> 00:29:18,949
In meditation, as I tried to bring their smiles into consciousness, a knot of tension would gather and I would recoil in agony.

257
00:29:20,431 --> 00:29:26,818
All my aversion was projected outwards onto them, seeing them as uncaring and even cruel.

258
00:29:27,961 --> 00:29:35,369
But with the practice of dropping the thoughts and noting each emotion, I would eventually unwind into compassion for my sorry state.

259
00:29:36,751 --> 00:29:45,182
In the kindly gaze of compassion, I could admit that the basis of all this turmoil was nothing to do with my friends at all.

260
00:29:46,144 --> 00:29:48,767
Instead, it was aversion to having lost my voice.

261
00:29:50,047 --> 00:29:59,981
With that admission, I could begin to see the value of moving on, accepting this new situation, working with it as best I could.

262
00:30:01,664 --> 00:30:12,560
At that stage, their smiles were seen as friendly and encouraging, and in my mind's eye, I could stretch out my hand gingerly towards them, let them lead me into my new life.

263
00:30:14,718 --> 00:30:22,730
So the Buddha's advice, find the best in your friends and try to copy it, is extremely valuable but very challenging.

264
00:30:23,510 --> 00:30:32,625
It brings up vanity, the way we cling haughtily to, I'm better than you, as our inner begrudger dismisses their virtue.

265
00:30:32,605 --> 00:30:40,817
Or as we collapse into the despair of I'm worse than you and we curl up into a ball of jealousy.

266
00:30:41,678 --> 00:30:50,190
Or we cling tight to the pleasant notion of we're just the same as our imagination pulls them into our gang.

267
00:30:51,351 --> 00:30:54,836
People we can understand and feel easy with.

268
00:30:55,897 --> 00:31:00,924
All of these, the Buddha says, are forms of vanity clinging to the notion I am.

269
00:31:02,676 --> 00:31:05,141
But this clinging doesn't do us any justice.

270
00:31:05,602 --> 00:31:15,096
We're trying to define who we are, fit ourselves into a box when in fact we're continually evolving and changing.

271
00:31:16,077 --> 00:31:18,320
We're on our journey to the end of suffering.

272
00:31:19,623 --> 00:31:29,038
It doesn't matter whether our friends are more or less developed, only that they're willing to help us along our path and we're willing to accept their help.

273
00:31:31,059 --> 00:31:32,101
And vice versa.

274
00:31:32,922 --> 00:31:34,242
That we're willing to help them.

275
00:31:36,045 --> 00:31:38,847
Any practical help must start with goodwill.

276
00:31:39,628 --> 00:31:44,834
Otherwise we'll end up trying to impose our supposed wisdom on them.

277
00:31:45,535 --> 00:31:48,438
So we bring them into our hearts in metta practice.

278
00:31:49,218 --> 00:31:51,800
The basis for spiritual friendship.

279
00:31:54,644 --> 00:31:58,688
I want to close with the final part of the Buddha's conversation with Ananda.

280
00:32:00,457 --> 00:32:10,535
And through this line of reasoning, one may know how admirable friendship, admirable companionship is actually the whole of the holy life.

281
00:32:12,178 --> 00:32:21,334
It is in dependence on me as an admirable friend that beings subject to ageing have gained release from ageing.

282
00:32:22,681 --> 00:32:30,771
He goes on to say the same about death, sorrow, lamentation, pain, distress and despair.

283
00:32:31,432 --> 00:32:48,354
Before concluding, it is through this line of reasoning that one may know how having admirable friendship, admirable companionship, admirable camaraderie is actually the whole of the holy life.

284
00:32:49,615 --> 00:32:52,619
Here the Buddha is inviting us to reflect on his life.

285
00:32:53,900 --> 00:33:01,211
and the many people who have benefited from his teaching, and thus to develop gratitude and admiration for him.

286
00:33:02,093 --> 00:33:07,923
This is a bit hard to put with his teaching of not-self.

287
00:33:07,942 --> 00:33:16,936
If nothing in his phenomenal being had any permanent substantial essence, what is it we are admiring and being grateful for?

288
00:33:18,689 --> 00:33:37,133
Although we can't identify a permanent essence with anything tangible about the Buddha, we can acknowledge that his dedication to finding an escape from dukkha and teaching others what he discovered had an enormous impact on the world.

289
00:33:38,174 --> 00:33:42,299
As a result, here we are on our own path to enlightenment.

290
00:33:43,698 --> 00:33:53,148
We can admire and be grateful for his dedication, energy, patience, compassion and all the other qualities that fuelled his spiritual life.

291
00:33:54,309 --> 00:33:58,675
Chief among these are his wisdom and awareness, satipanya.

292
00:34:00,798 --> 00:34:08,507
Using these faculties he discovered that which is unborn, undying, the end of all suffering.

293
00:34:11,557 --> 00:34:22,891
And while we can't paint a mental picture of whatever in him enjoys the perfect piece of Nibbana, we can each in our own way attempt to take that mystery to heart.

294
00:34:23,952 --> 00:34:32,563
For myself, this would mean allowing myself to wonder, what is it in him that is unborn, undying, the end of suffering?

295
00:34:33,485 --> 00:34:34,706
Of course, I have no answers.

296
00:34:35,608 --> 00:34:41,514
Sometimes my mind conjures up a bright light and I feel myself basking in its warmth.

297
00:34:41,967 --> 00:34:50,737
Often the initial pleasure turns to some form of dukkha, perhaps grief that I can't grasp onto that light, hold it forever in my heart.

298
00:34:52,320 --> 00:35:00,610
But the grief is sensed as healing, teaching me to let go of attachment to any image or notion of what enlightenment might be.

299
00:35:01,851 --> 00:35:08,159
Recognising this, gratitude comes up and a deeper commitment to this contemplation.

300
00:35:09,338 --> 00:35:13,103
Now of course our begrudging attitudes show up here too.

301
00:35:14,585 --> 00:35:17,230
Who does he think he is asking everyone to adore him?

302
00:35:17,871 --> 00:35:19,333
Does he think he's God Almighty?

303
00:35:20,835 --> 00:35:22,737
But we know the drill.

304
00:35:22,757 --> 00:35:24,360
Know thoughts as thoughts.

305
00:35:25,402 --> 00:35:26,403
Feel the feelings.

306
00:35:27,284 --> 00:35:30,110
Trust things to evolve in the light of awareness.

307
00:35:31,371 --> 00:35:38,282
As I take on this practice what happens is that I feel myself developing a personal relationship with the Buddha.

308
00:35:39,697 --> 00:35:59,623
For example, my imagination can be drawn towards the details of his life, remembering his shock when he realised the futility of his princely life, for example, seeing him say his last goodbye to his wife and son, creeping out of the palace to take up the life of a wandering ascetic.

309
00:36:02,588 --> 00:36:08,876
Later on, after years of hardship, accepting the rice milk from Sujata,

310
00:36:10,561 --> 00:36:12,887
That's a very inspiring image for me.

311
00:36:13,809 --> 00:36:20,588
I would see it as the moment he recognised that his humanity and bodily needs form part of his spiritual path.

312
00:36:21,817 --> 00:36:30,393
Another very touching moment for me is during his last temptation before enlightenment, when Mara, his inner begrudger, sneers.

313
00:36:31,255 --> 00:36:33,199
What makes you think you could be enlightened?

314
00:36:34,121 --> 00:36:35,664
What have you done to merit that?

315
00:36:35,885 --> 00:36:37,068
Who do you think you are?

316
00:36:38,048 --> 00:36:41,817
This is the hindrance of self-doubt, a challenge for every human being.

317
00:36:42,994 --> 00:36:47,601
In all the other temptations, he was able to sit still and not be swayed.

318
00:36:48,362 --> 00:36:51,186
But here his resolution is shaking.

319
00:36:52,387 --> 00:36:54,449
He feels the need of support.

320
00:36:55,190 --> 00:37:02,960
He stretches his hand down to touch the earth, calling it as witness to his right to come to the end of suffering.

321
00:37:04,443 --> 00:37:10,791
As I contemplate these and other stories from the life of the Buddha he becomes a more tangible presence in my life.

322
00:37:11,813 --> 00:37:17,460
Imagining his serenity under the rose apple tree I feel serene.

323
00:37:18,483 --> 00:37:23,990
Imagining his courage in leaving home I feel myself grow in courage.

324
00:37:24,010 --> 00:37:34,045
Seeing him reach down to the earth in his moment of self-doubt I feel myself as part of the earth reassuring him, encouraging him to press on

325
00:37:35,425 --> 00:37:44,635
This growing sense of friendship, companionship, camaraderie makes it a bit easier to contemplate his enlightened state.

326
00:37:45,876 --> 00:37:58,269
The touch of friendship extends beyond my understanding, encouraging me to make peace with the mystery of the unborn, undying, the end of suffering.

327
00:37:58,289 --> 00:38:03,255
There is a growing trust that whatever it is or isn't, there is nothing to fear.

328
00:38:04,518 --> 00:38:06,400
This is the practice of devotion.

329
00:38:07,302 --> 00:38:11,909
Those of us brought up in Christianity will be familiar with the approach.

330
00:38:12,730 --> 00:38:21,664
Contemplating the life of Jesus, as we say the Rosary for example, devotion is a way of opening the heart.

331
00:38:21,684 --> 00:38:26,610
It's a form of metta practice, where we make the Buddha the object of our metta.

332
00:38:27,733 --> 00:38:30,677
One teacher calls it falling in love with the Buddha.

333
00:38:32,733 --> 00:38:35,597
Now, of course, falling in love is not plain sailing.

334
00:38:35,737 --> 00:38:38,760
It can evoke inner, great inner turmoil.

335
00:38:40,724 --> 00:38:43,367
We can fall in and out of love at a great rate.

336
00:38:44,168 --> 00:38:52,059
Wandering mind, dullness, restlessness, aversion, all the hindrances come up as we bring the Buddha to mind.

337
00:38:53,400 --> 00:39:00,309
At times we'll be able to simply note these and then come back to the main focus, the Buddha.

338
00:39:01,369 --> 00:39:10,324
At times we have to give our full attention to whatever hindrance is uppermost, trusting that it will eventually burn itself out in the light of awareness.

339
00:39:11,465 --> 00:39:17,916
So we can switch between devotion and mindfulness as appropriate.

340
00:39:17,936 --> 00:39:19,278
It's like any relationship.

341
00:39:19,659 --> 00:39:22,643
At times we can be completely focused on the other.

342
00:39:23,264 --> 00:39:29,014
At times we need to withdraw and tend to ourselves, maybe to lick our wounds.

343
00:39:30,547 --> 00:39:37,724
This retreat is an ideal opportunity to follow the Buddha's teaching on Kalyana Mita, our spiritual friendship.

344
00:39:39,509 --> 00:39:44,000
If it weren't for the people around us, we wouldn't be spending so many hours a day in meditation.

345
00:39:44,762 --> 00:39:47,188
So everyone here is our spiritual friend.

346
00:39:48,619 --> 00:39:55,210
We could devote a portion of our meditation practice to bringing each other into our hearts.

347
00:39:56,411 --> 00:39:58,855
Being grateful for our connection within the group.

348
00:39:59,896 --> 00:40:03,742
Let's vow to look for the best in one another and copy that.

349
00:40:03,762 --> 00:40:09,532
And for those of you who like falling in love, then give in to the temptation.

350
00:40:09,931 --> 00:40:11,134
Fall in love with the Buddha.

351
00:40:13,222 --> 00:40:19,032
Or you might prefer a somewhat more Buddhist phrase, become the Buddha within.

